<h2>1. Robins</h2>

<p>The bare trees allow a number of natural wonders to be seen, which would otherwise be hidden by leaves. The most striking of these is the robin, with its characteristic red chest. I find that robins, especially in the winter, have an air of sass about them as they cheerfully sing.</p>
<p>On a trip to Edinburgh, one flew down and landed straight in front of us. It stared at us then hopped about, striking many poses as if to say &ldquo;I am wonderful, look at me!&rdquo;. We took many photos as it puffed out its little chest triumphantly, and it made this quote from the Secret Garden seem very apt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;<strong>Nothing in the world is quite as adorably lovely as a robin when he shows off - and they are nearly always doing it.</strong>&rdquo;</p>
<p>So have a look among trees for flashes of red, and listen out for sounds of birdsong, as a fabulous robin might be near.</p>

