<h2>4. Hazel Catkins</h2>

<p>There are so many interesting parts about the natural world, far more than we get taught about in school. When I was growing up I would sit under a tree in the school yard. It had these wonderful little things dangling off them, which I&rsquo;d often play with. They looked like someone had threaded lots of tiny flat discs onto the ends of the branches.</p>
<p>The tree was a birch tree, and my mum told me that the fun little dangles were catkins. Surprisingly they&rsquo;re a type of flower and can come in all sorts of different ways from scaly to fluffy. They appear before the trees get back their spring green leaves, and the tree that gets them first is the hazel. From these catkins the tree will make its tasty hazelnuts, to be found many months later around August.</p>

